  "text": "All data were displayed and digitized with commercially available data acquisition software (Windaq; Dataq Instruments). BFV, MAP, and CO 2 waveforms were resampled at 100 Hz using a custom MATLAB program. Beat-to-beat R-R interval was determined from the R wave of the ECG or from the peak blood pressure waveform. MAP and mean BFV were determined from the integrals of each . Individual responses were averaged across individuals to obtain mean responses for MAP and BFV to each trial. Cerebrovascular resistance index (CVR i ) was calculated as the ratio of MAP to mean BFV in the PCA and MCA arterial territories. Coherence, gains, and phases were calculated using the MAP and normalized BFV signal autospectra in the low (0.03-0.07 Hz), high (0.07-0.15 Hz), and cardiac (Ϸ1 Hz) frequency ranges. Detailed methods of mathematical calculations are described in our previous study. [CITATION_1] Gain in the low-frequency range (0.03-0.07 Hz) is considered to be autoregulatory in nature because autoregulation is a relatively slow process and can take several seconds to engage. 14 Increased transfer function gains indicate greater transmission of arterial blood pressure fluctuation to cerebral blood flow, suggesting impaired autoregulation. Previous work has found decreased autoregulation during cardiovascular stress using this methodology. [CITATION_2] In addition, other groups have examined the phase shift between blood pressure and velocity to assess autoregulation. An angle approaching 0°can be interpreted as absence of autoregulation because flow changes are occurring at exactly the same time as pressure changes, suggesting passive modulation of flow by pressure. In contrast, Ϫ90°is considered optimal autoregulation because changes in flow are delayed presumably because of autoregulatory mechanisms. [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] Because gains in the cardiac frequency (ie, Ϸ1 Hz) are occurring too rapidly to be autoregulatory, they represent passive transmission of arterial blood pressure to BFV and likely reflect the stiffness of vessels. For examination of autoregulation in the PCA and MCA territories while seated with eyes open, 5 minutes of data were analyzed. For comparison between eyes open and closed, steadystate 1-minute data sets were examined. Previous work has used similar 1-minute data sets to assess the linear dynamic relationship between MAP and BFV via fast-Fourier transform-based methodology. 18 -20 These short data sets are adequate to examine autoregulatory function because, according to the Nyquist-Shannon theory, ",
